Whinsley Masara, Chronicle Reporter FIVE suspected poachers were arrested and one of them is receiving treatment at Mpilo Central Hospital in Bulawayo after he was shot at Matopos National Park. The Anti-Poaching Police Team and game rangers heard gunshots within the national park in the early hours of Monday after poachers had shot down one wildebeest and two kudus worth $4 600.The anti-poaching team exchanged fire with one of the suspected poachers and he was injured.The injured suspect is admitted to Mpilo Central Hospital.Matabeleland South Police spokesperson Inspector Philisani Ndebele confirmed the incident. I can confirm receiving a report of five men who were arrested for poaching. A wildebeest, two kudus and a firearm were recovered at the scene. There was an exchange fire which resulted in one of the poachers being injured. He is in a stable condition and is admitted at Mpilo Central Hospital. Investigations are underway, he said. We urge members of the public to shun poaching as the law will descend heavily on them. These animals belong to us as a nation and our responsibility is to guard them jealously. Insp Ndebele identified the suspected poachers as Levi Dube (36) of Richmond suburb, Ray Sibanda (23) of Trenance suburb, Icroln Moffat (24) of Bradfield suburb, James Greenland (32) of Trenance suburb, all in Bulawayo and Leon Spenser (23) of Ticher s Farm along the Bulawayo-Victoria Falls Road, near the city.A source at the national park said the anti-poaching team was alerted to the presence of the suspected poachers by gunfire. There was an exchange of fire between the police and the poachers and one of them got injured during the process. One of them was arrested after he failed to catch up with their Mazda BT 50 vehicle as they were escaping. He assisted police to arrest the others, said the source.@winnie_masara